   (Message) The program crashes due to a use-after-free error caused by
   capturing an iterator into a `std::vector<int>` before a loop that performs
   many `push_back` operations. The iterator `it` is initialized to `v.begin() +
   2` on line 10. However, within the loop (line 11–13), `v.push_back(i)` is
   called 1000 times, which is well beyond the initial capacity of the vector
   (which, for a vector of 4 elements, is likely 4 or 8). This triggers
   reallocation of the internal storage. When reallocation occurs, all existing
   iterators, pointers, and references to elements in the vector are
   invalidated. The iterator `it`, which was captured before the loop, now
   points to memory that has been freed or overwritten. After the loop, the
   program attempts to dereference `it`, causing a heap-use-after-free violation
   that is detected by AddressSanitizer. The `print` commands fail because the
   debugger cannot access local variables once control has returned from `main`,
   but the evidence from the source and the nature of the error confirms that
   `it` is dangling after `push_back` reallocation.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `program.cpp:10` — The iterator `it` is captured from `v` before
   a series of `push_back` calls that may reclaim the vector's internal storage;
   when reallocation occurs, the iterator becomes invalidated and its use after
   the loop results in undefined behavior (use-after-free).
   
   LOCAL FIX: Replace the raw iterator with a value-based access pattern.
   Instead of capturing the iterator, compute the value of the element at index
   2 directly after the loop. In `program.cpp`, modify line 10 and the final
   dereference:
   
   ```cpp
   auto it = v.begin() + 2;
   for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {
       v.push_back(i);
   }
   // Replace this:
   // std::cout << *it << std::endl;
   // With:
   std::cout << v[2] << std::endl;
   ```
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Use `std::vector::at()` or `std::vector::operator[]` instead of
   storing iterators when the vector is subject to modification. Better yet,
   adopt a design pattern where indices are used instead of iterators in
   contexts where reallocations are possible. Prefer `std::span` or similar
   bounded views if C++20 is available, or refactor the logic to avoid holding
   iterators across operations that modify the container. This enforces at
   compile time (via rules) that iterator lifetime is not extended past
   container mutation, preventing such errors.
   
